# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-carthage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] An independence referendum was held in French Algeria on 1 July 1962.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] It followed French approval of the Évian Accords in an April referendum.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] Voters were asked whether Algeria should become an independent state, co-operating with France; 99.72% voted in favour with a voter turnout of 91.88%.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] Following the referendum, France declared Algeria to be independent on 3 July; the decision was published in the official journal the following day, and Algerian leaders declared 5 July (the 132nd anniversary of the French arrival in Algiers) to be Independence Day.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] When Algeria ceased to be part of France it also ceased being part of the European Communities.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] The Algerian War was started by members of the National Liberation Front (FLN) with the Toussaint Rouge attacks on 1 November 1954.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] Conflicts proliferated in France, including the May 1958 Algerian crisis that led to the fall of the Fourth Republic.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] French forces used brutal means of attempting to suppress Algerian nationalists, alienating support in metropolitan France and discrediting French prestige abroad.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] In 1960, French President Charles de Gaulle agreed to negotiations with the FLN after major demonstrations in Algiers and other cities.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] A 1961 referendum on allowing self-determination for Algeria was approved by 75% of voters (including 70% of those voting in Algeria).
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] Negotiations concluded with the signing of the Évian Accords in March 1962, which were approved by 91% of voters in a referendum on 8 April.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] In accordance with the Évian accords (Chapter III.3) France was allowed to maintain its Mers El Kébir naval base for fifteen years.
[src:ancient-carthage/1962-algerian-independence-referendum] However, all forces were withdrawn in 1967.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] The **1965 Algerian coup d'état** brought Colonel Houari Boumédiène to power as Chairman of the Revolutionary Council in Algeria.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] The bloodless *coup d'état* saw Algeria's first President, Ahmed Ben Bella, arrested and his closest supporters imprisoned by Boumédiène and his allies, principally in the Algerian Land Forces.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] The arrest of Ben Bella occurred on 19 June 1965.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Following the Algerian War of Independence (1954–1962), with the help of then Chief of Staff Houari Boumédiène and the National Liberation Army (ALN), Ahmed Ben Bella was elected as Prime Minister in September 1962, ousting former Prime Minister Benyoucef Benkhedda.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Owing to his support of Ben Bella, Boumédiène was appointed Defense Minister by Ben Bella and remained in this position until 1976.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] From 1962 to 1965, Ben Bella governed in an often erratic manner and centralized more and more government institutions by appointing himself the Secretary General of the Party, minister of the Interior, and the head of other bodies.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Concerns of Ben Bella's demagogic behavior pervaded the Algerian government, with many government cadres coming to Boumédiène to voice their worries and complaints about the President.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Boumédiène spent time traveling in early 1965, making trips to Baghdad, Cairo, and Moscow.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] In Cairo, he represented Algeria at a summit of Arab countries and met with Soviet leadership in Moscow.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] In April 1965, Ben Bella ordered local police to report directly to him rather than through the normal channels in the Ministry of Interior.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] The interior minister, Ahmed Medeghri, one of Boumédiène's closest associates, resigned in protest.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] By late May, Boumédiène had begun having serious conversations with leading government figures, mostly in the army, on removing Ben Bella.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] By mid June, there was a feeling of emergency within the army, leading many commanders to agree to execute a plan that they had no real knowledge of.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] The coup plan was designed carefully, with Boumédiène's goal being to execute "the most elegant coup d'etat" in recent memory.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] A friend of Ben Bella attempted to warn him about the coup on the 16th, but Ben Bella dismissed him.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] "*Marionnettes* (puppets) such as them are not capable of carrying out a coup," he replied.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] On the evening of 18 June 1965, the leaders of the coup set the plan to remove Ben Bella in motion.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] That night, Boumédiène remained at his office where he supervised the coup execution that was broadly entrusted to commander Chabou, one of the first conspirators.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] As president, Ben Bella took residence at a place named the ‘Villa Joly’, located in Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Typically, guards of the Compagnies nationales de securite (CNS) protected the compound and the guards changed shifts at 8:00pm every night; however, on 18 June Ahmed Draia, director of security, ensured that the new guards for the night shift were *djounoud* loyal to the military.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] At 1:00am, Boumédiène ordered tanks to be deployed throughout the capital at strategic positions such as Grande Poste d'Alger, Radio-Télévision Algérienne, and Place de l'Émir-Abdelkader (the seat of the party at the time).
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] The film *The Battle of Algiers* was being shot in the capital at the time, and many onlookers thought the military movement was connected to shooting the movie.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Around 1:30am, Tahar Zbiri, Said Abid, and colonel Abbes approached Villa Joly and were let in by the replacement guards at the entrance.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Zbiri reported to Boumédiène: "Mission accomplished." Ben Bella would remain under house arrest until 1980 and would not return publicly to Algeria until 1990.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] By 3:00am on 19 June, the coup was effectively over with no bloodshed.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] On 19 June, Boumédiène broadcast a radio address which stated that the removal of Ben Bella was necessary to ensure continuity of the revolution.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] He accused Ben Bella of attempting to hijack the Afro-Asian Unity Conference for personal gain without regard to the other countries of the organization.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Boumédiène announced that Algeria would not be able to host the conference under these circumstances but expressed his support for the ideals of the organization.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] However, the Pan-African Cultural Festival (PANAF) with attendees from all over the world, including the Black Panthers, would be organized by the Boumédiène administration in 1969 and held in Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] In the speech he also called Ben Bella a charlatan and an adventurist, possibly a reference to Ben Bella's support of Niger rebels using Algeria as a safe haven for their activity against the Diori government in Niger, something Boumédiène never supported.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Another radio announcement by Kaïd Ahmed on the same day stated that the "instability, demagogy, anarchy, lies, and improvisation" of Ben Bella's government were over.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] On 19 and 20 June people began protesting against the coup and chanting pro-Ben Bella slogans; the new government attempted to disperse the protests, but the local police, not military elements were used to maintain order in most instances.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] In Algiers, between two and three thousand people roamed the streets, calling for the assassination of Boumédiène.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Radio addresses repeatedly called for calm, and sometimes threatened the protesters.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Several people were arrested, including 50 French far-left supporters of Ben Bella.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] On 5 July, Boumédiène announced the creation of the Revolutionary Council (RC) with himself serving as president of the RC, Minister of Defense, and President of the Council of Ministers.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Boumédiène announced that the RC's two main goals were economic self-reliance and independent of foreign influence to the Algerian people and internally the RC sought to end regionalism, solidify the state, and to reform the wilayahs.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] Boumédiène's first travel abroad was in September 1965 to Casablanca at an Arab summit followed by a summit for the Organization of African Unity (today the African Union) in October.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] The RC began the country's first census in December at the same time Boumédiène visited Moscow for the second time in 1965.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] On the anniversary of the coup, he addressed the Algerian people again and reemphasized his goals to end regionalism, move progressively toward socialism, keep Algeria 'Algerian', resist foreign influence, support former freedom fighters, and remove remaining French bases from the Sahara.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] One year after the coup, Boumédiène pursued these goals by visiting the Eastern, Western, Tiaret, and Oasis wilayahs and progressively nationalizing industries such as mining to guard against foreign interference.
[src:ancient-carthage/1965-algerian-coup-d-état] He also reorganized the FLN in June 1966.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] The **1987 Tunisian coup d'état** involved the bloodless ousting of the aging president of Tunisia Habib Bourguiba on 7 November 1987, and his replacement as president by his recently appointed prime minister, Zine El Abidine Ben Ali.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] The action was justified by reference to Bourguiba's failing health and Article 57 of the country's constitution.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Reports later surfaced to indicate that the Italian intelligence services had been involved in planning it.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Sources sometimes identify the 1987 coup as the "Révolution de jasmin" (*Jasmin Revolution*) as the jasmine flower is considered a symbol of Tunisia.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] However, more recent sources also use the same term to identify the 2011 Tunisian Revolution.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] During the night of 6 November 1987, a group of seven doctors signed a medical report attesting to the mental incapacity of Bourguiba.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] At the same time, Bourguiba demanded new trials for 15 suspected Islamists, and that all but three of them be hanged by the following weekend.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] When this order became known, a number of Tunisian political leaders, including longtime supporters of Bourguiba, feared that Bourguiba was no longer acting or thinking rationally.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Later, one human rights activist said that if the orders had been carried out, it would have triggered a civil war.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] In justification of the coup, Prime Minister Ben Ali invoked Article 57 of the constitution, as he assumed power.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] He rapidly emerged, therefore, not merely as the constitutional president, but also as the commander in chief of the army.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] The next day the new president addressed the nation on Radio Tunis.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] He paid tribute to the huge sacrifices that his predecessor had made, supported by brave men, in his service to the liberation and development of Tunisia.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] At the same time Ben Ali took the opportunity to make a declaration: "In the times in which we live it is not longer enough to put up either with presidencies for life or with automatic succession for the head of state, under a system from which the people are excluded.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Fulvio Martini, a former head of the Italian Intelligence Service, gave an interview to the newspaper *la Repubblica* on 11 October 1997 in which he asserted that Italian Intelligence had played an important role in the removal of Bourgiba.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] "Everything began with the visit of the Italian Prime Minister Bettino Craxi to Algeria in 1984", he explained.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] "The Algerians were nervous about growing instability in Tunisia and were ready to intervene" because of the risks the situation presented to their own strategic interests.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] This meant that the Algerian army was ready to invade the part of Tunisia crossed by the natural-gas pipeline transporting Algerian gas to Sicily.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Martini continued: "In 1985 Prime Minister Craxi asked me to go to Algeria and establish contact with the security services there ... in order to avert any sudden move by Algeria.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] That was the start of a lengthy foreign policy operation in which the security services played a central role.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] In the end the parties agreed that General Ben Ali would be better able to guarantee the stability of Tunisia than Bourguiba." Martini added: "We suggested this solution to the Algerians and they discussed it with the Libyans.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] I went to talk to the French [...but...] the French security chief at that time, René Imbot reacted with arrogance, and simply stated that we Italians should not become involved, because Tunisia was part of France's imperial legacy".
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] The priority was to organise a coup as invisible as possible, and this gave rise to the idea of a "medical coup".
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Italy would guarantee to support a Ben Ali takeover, and this choice was also approved by Libya and Algeria.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] "It is true that Italy replaced Bourguiba with Ben Ali" Martini agreed after 10 October 1999 when *la Repubblica* referred to a report that Martini had revealed before a parliamentary commission on 6 October 1999.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] On the other hand, Craxi disputed any involvement by the Italian Security Services.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Speaking in 1999 to Agence France-Press in Tunis: "There was no Italian manoeuvring or interference in the events that carried President Ben Ali to power in 1987".
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] The closeness of Craxi's own complicated and long standing relationship with the Tunisian political establishment led commentators to doubt his words, but the French journal Le Monde found no evidence against his version.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Craxi remained a close friend of Ben Ali, and died, while being prosecuted by the Italian justice system for the Tangentopoli scandal, in Tunisia (2000).
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] Ben Ali took control of the ruling Socialist Destourian Party, renamed it and transformed it into the Democratic Constitutional Rally.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] The promised elections took place in 1989 and were won by the new party.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] In principle, Ben Ali followed similar policies to Bourguiba, positioning himself as the spiritual successor to his superannuated predecessor.
[src:ancient-carthage/1987-tunisian-coup-d-état] He remained in power for 23 years until 2011, when he was deposed in the Tunisian Revolution.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The **1988 October Riots** were a series of street-level disturbances and riotous demonstrations by Algerian youth, which started on 5 October 1988 and ended on the 11th.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The riots were "the most serious" since Algeria's independence", and involved thousands of youth who "took control of the streets".
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Riots started in Algiers and spread to other cities, resulting in about 500 deaths and 1000 wounded although the official death count reports that 159 were killed with 154 protesters injured.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The first, and most prominent argument among Western journalists is that the riots stemmed from recent economic troubles in Algeria.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The rising prices, the high rate of unemployment among youth, and austerity measures announced by the government fed the desire to express their discontent.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Between 1985 and 1987, the unemployment rate increased rapidly from 658,000 to 1,200,000 while the unemployment rate was anticipated to reach 31.7% of the population by the year 2000.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Coupled with the demographic changes due to the high fertility rate since Algeria's independence, there was a significant subsection of the population between the ages of 0-14, accounting for 44.35% of the population in 1988.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] In light of the continuous reduction in fuel prices, a significant source of income for the country, it is evident how the link between an economic downturn and the outburst of protests is formed.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] With no evident sign of economic progress in sight, the youth, most of them from low-income neighborhoods, took to the streets to advocate for their basic human right—an equal chance to succeed in life.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] However, this analysis falls short in light of the "lack of economic grievances" from the rioters.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] There were no official declarations made concerning their economic objectives.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Despite President Chadli's speech on 10 October in which he announced the government's plan to proceed with the widely unpopular austerity measures, and price reductions for necessities, the riots came to a halt that evening.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The second argument is a deep political contempt for President Chadli Bendjedid and the FLN government.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Rioters were recorded saying "we don't want butter or pepper, we want a leader we can respect".
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The use of the words butter and pepper, which are two staple products highlights the flaws of the economic determinism argument.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Despite their economic hardships, the rioters were pushing for honest leaders, rather than economic reforms.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Similarly, the lawyers who supported the young men argued that the riots were a result of the lack of formal avenues to freely and peacefully express their frustrations.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The police and the civil administration were put under military control and torture of detainees at the police academy was reported.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The state of emergency was decreed on 6 October and a curfew was established that ran from midnight to six o'clock in the morning (starting on 8 October the curfew was not enforced until 8 o'clock at night).
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Police were taunted as "Jews" by the demonstrators, a comment on the intifada in Israel.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] On 9 October, an anonymous tract was distributed to the youth which called for a march the next day.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] This march, under the leadership of imam Ali Benhadj led to violent repressions resulting in the deaths of 30 protesters.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Torture was also used as a means of discouraging protesters, including sodomy, mutilation, and electrocution.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] In general, the riots were directed at the increasing social despair – to a large extent, the result of oil prices dropping sharply the preceding years – and at the slow pace of economic and political reform.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The protests were violently repressed, but set in motion a process of internal power struggles and public criticism.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Following the riots, the Bendjedid government promised political reforms with a "greater democratisation of political action" and "political and institutional changes".
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] On 13 October, President Chadli announced that the 1976 Constitution would be revised through a referendum on 3 November.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] This referendum had a participation rate of 83.1% with 92.27% of the voters in favor of its revision.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The Constitution of 1989 was submitted to a referendum on 23 February 1989, ushering in what some believe was a new chapter of Algerian history.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] In comparison to the previous constitution, the 1989 constitution demonstrated the new direction of the Algerian government.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The reference to socialism is not found in the new constitution and the recognition of freedom of the individual replaces the recognition of the freedom of the people found in the previous constitution.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] In Article 1, Algeria is referred to as a "socialist state" while the 1989 constitution asserts that it is a "democratic and people's republic".
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Similarly, Chapter 2 which dedicated fifteen articles to explaining the government's commitment to socialism is completely removed.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The transition from socialism to democracy is often interpreted as a new openness to pluralism.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] This analysis is supported by the introduction of Article 42 which states all citizens have the "right to create associations with a political character".
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] This article gives credibility to opposing political parties such as the Parti d'Avant-Garde Socialistes (PAGS) and the Front Islamique du Salut (FIS) to emerge on the scene.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] Nevertheless, according to Aït-Aoudia, this puts these political reforms into question by interrogating the possibility of truly reforming a one-party state into a democracy.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] She argues that by making the FLN party the apparatus of the state, there is a lack of precedent on how to create a democratic system where multiple political parties can occupy various positions peacefully.
[src:ancient-carthage/1988-october-riots] The constitution of 1989 gives a new role to the army relegating it to defending the national independence of Algeria.The new constitution puts an emphasis on religion in its preamble, stating that Algeria is a "land of Islam".
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] In the post civil war period of the 2000s ‘Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb’ (‘AQIM’), an Algerian Islamic extremist group, rose to prominence and was responsible for a number of acts of terrorism in Algeria and the Northern African region.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] This was relevant in relation to world politics at the time as it tied in with the USA's ‘War on Terror’, and lead to cooperation between the two nations in global counterterrorism attempts.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The 2000s in Algeria was also impacted by the 2001 'Black Spring’, an uprising by members of the Kabyle ethnic group, as well as the 2001 Algerian floods which destroyed infrastructure, displaced families and resulted in a significant death toll.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The civil war officially ended when peace was established in 2002.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] This came after the presidential elections of April 1999 and the controversial election of Abdelaziz Bouteflika who according to Journalist Ramy Allahoum “spent his first years as president trying to end the civil war”.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Bouteflika successfully achieved this in the first half of the decade by offering an official amnesty to the Islamic Guerrilla fighters who had fought in opposition to the government during the war.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] This amnesty was offered only to those who had been accused of non-violent crimes, and did not include those who had engaged in crimes such as rape, murder or bombing.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The 'Civil Concord' law was adopted by nationwide referendum in September 1999 as a means of ending the war and establishing the proposed amnesty for 'Islamic Salvation Front' ('FIS') fighters.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Although highly favoured by voters, at the time the law's effectiveness was criticised by certain non-government organisations.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The ICG stated the policy had "failed" in their 2001 report *'The Civil Concord: a peace initiative wasted'*.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] A later report published in 2008, after the civil war had ended, by the Library of Congress: Federal Research Division states that "The reconciliation by no means ended all violence, but it reduced violence to manageable levels".
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] In 2005 the ‘Charter for Peace and National Reconciliation’ further enforced the amnesty agreement for "all but the most violent participants in the Islamist Uprising" and was again voted highly in favour of by the Algerian public.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] This legislative action further stabilised and significantly reduced violence in the country after official termination of the war in 2002.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Some felt that despite the tactical success of these laws, they failed to recognise the losses experienced by many Algerians during the war, and did not provide adequate punishment or retribution to those responsible for the violence.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] President Bouteflika remained president for the entirety of the 2000s decade, after being re-elected to serve another five-year term in 2004 and 2009.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The political system of the country during this period shifted to a slightly more democratic style government under Bouteflika's leadership, as opposed to the strictly "military rule" of the civil war period.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] However, controversy has surrounded the election and reelection of President Bouteflika over the decade.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] His 1999 election was the subject of much criticism after just one day prior to the election all six of the other candidates pulled out with accusations of military fraud.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] According to a report from The Guardian "The United States called the polls a lost opportunity for progress towards democracy".
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] In 2004 Bouteflika's reelection was considered more legitimate yet still not completely transparent, as stated by Carol Migdalovitz in her *CRS Report for Congress,* there was "some manipulation of the political process but without blatant fraud".
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Bouteflika's 2009 reelection was too considered an illegitimate win with Carnegie Middle East Centre reporting that he "used money to buy support" and that the 90.2% vote was "far too high to be credible".
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Bouteflika went on to be reelected once more in 2014 following the end of the 2000s decade and has, despite controversy, been praised by many for his genuine success in bringing about an end to the war, restoring stability to the country, and expanding foreign and economic policy.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Despite the reduction in violence from the civil war, terrorism rose in prominence during the 2000s period, both nationally and globally.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The Algerian Islamic extremist group ‘Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb’ (‘AQIM’) emerged from the Islamic Guerrilla forces which fought in opposition to the government during the Algerian civil war.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] In 2003 the group formerly known as ‘Armed Islamic Group’ (‘GIA’) gained international recognition as being part of the Al-Qaeda group, and officially identified itself as ‘AQIM’ in 2007.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The group was responsible for a number of violent terrorist acts in Algeria and Northern Africa which mostly targeted westerners as victims. ‘AQIM’, like other global terrorist groups in the 2000s, utilised new technology and the internet in order to gain influence and carry out their attacks.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Extremist Islamic terrorism in Algeria during this period was particularly relevant to the global politics of the decade, which was heavily influenced by the 2001 9/11 terrorist attacks and American President George Bush's ‘War on Terror’.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Algeria and the USA cooperated in counterterrorism efforts during the 2000s and according to Professor Mhand Berkouk “Several countries became interested in the Algerian experience and the expertise the country had gained in counterterrorism operations”.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Bouteflika made two visits to the White House in 2001 following the September attacks, once in July and once in November.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Bouteflika has been accredited by Carnegie Middle East Centre with "Reinvigorating the country's foreign policy", both through cooperation with the United States and its growing role in Africa.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Along with bringing an end to the war and reducing violence, Bouteflika's "primary task was to rebuild the country and its economy" according to the BBC.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] By 2004, at the time of his second election, the president had reduced debt and economic growth was at its "highest since the 1980's" according to the New York Times.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Unemployment continued to be a major issue throughout the decade, particularly among young people.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The New York Times reported the countries unemployment level was at 25% in 2003.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] By 2009 unemployment was recorded at 75% of people under the age of 30 by Carnegie, Middle East Centre.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] In early 2001 riots broke out in the Kayblia region of Algeria as the native Berber people of the area fought to gain increased recognition of their traditional language and culture.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The riots, known as the ‘Black Spring’, lasted up to 10 days and where responsible for between 40 and 80 deaths, with some controversy surrounding the validity of the recorded death toll.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The catalyst for the riots was the death of a young Berber person who was shot while being held in custody by the national rural police, the Gendarmerie Nationale, in April 2001.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] This event caused particular outrage amongst the Berber community as it came during preparations for the 21st anniversary of the 1980 ‘Berber Spring’ uprising.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] As a result, strikes and demonstrations have gained popularity and frequency in the Kayblia, especially amongst the youth of the region.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Primary concerns of the protesters where the recognition of the Thamazighth language, restitution for the deaths of Kabylia people, removal of armed forces and autonomy for the Kabylia region.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The 2001 ‘Black Spring’ has been referred to as one of the “deadliest events in the movements history” by Journalist Yasmina Allouche, as it spurred over 4 years of political unrest in the country lasting until early 2006.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] In the wake of the riots, Algeria experienced its largest demonstration in history, with more than 1 million protestors meeting on the 11 June 2001.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The ‘Black Spring’ was a turning point in the ongoing history of the movement and left a legacy of political support for the Berber minority, such as formation of the transnational ‘Citizens Movement’.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] On the 10th of April 2002 the Berber language Tamazight was officially recognised and constitutionalised as a national language.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] In November 2001 Algeria was struck by “its worst flooding in years” as described by journalist Abdelmalek Touati.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The floods affected the Northern region of Algeria, where precipitation levels are highest in the country.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] It was recorded by the UN Office for Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) that up to 751 people where killed, and up to 10, 000 families where effected by the ‘devastating’ flooding.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] The effected area was submerged in mud, leaving significant damage to roads, houses, schools and businesses, however ‘no danger of water-borne diseases’ was reported according to the OCHA.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] In the wake of this damage, Algeria was supported in its clean up and recovery by a number of nations, such as Sweden, France and Qatar.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] UNICEF and UNDP also contributed equivalent to US$3 million to the country in order to provide assistance.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] However, the National Algerian government was criticised by its people for its delayed response and lack of preparation for the natural disaster.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] Overall the country was left deeply effected by the 2001 floods.
[src:ancient-carthage/2000s-in-algeria] It was recorded in 2005 that ‘Approximately half the Algerian population lives below the poverty line’ and that the country ‘ranked 104 out of 177 countries in...overall well-being’ according to the United Nations’ human development index.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The **2010–2012 Algerian protests** were a series of protests taking place throughout Algeria, lasting from 28 December 2010 to 10 January 2012.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The protests were inspired by similar protests across the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Causes cited by the protesters included unemployment, the lack of housing, food-price inflation, corruption, restrictions on freedom of speech and poor living conditions.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] While localized protests were already commonplace over previous years, extending into December 2010, an unprecedented wave of simultaneous protests and riots, sparked by sudden rises in staple food prices, erupted all over the country starting in January 2011.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] These were quelled by government measures to lower food prices, but were followed by a wave of self-immolations, most of them in front of government buildings.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Meanwhile, protests by unemployed youth, typically citing unemployment, *hogra* (oppression), and infrastructure problems, resumed, occurring almost daily in towns scattered all over the country.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] After the riots of 1988, the Algerian government had moved towards democracy, holding free elections.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] However, when the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) won the first free parliamentary election in 1991, the military staged a coup d'état, voided the election results, declared a state of emergency which remained in force until 2011, and arrested the FIS leadership.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] This led to the founding of the Armed Islamic Groups (GIA) and the ten-year Algerian Civil War, in which an estimated 250,000 people were killed.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] With the unchallenged election of Abdelaziz Bouteflika as president in 1999, civilian government was nominally restored.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Violence died down as both guerrillas and soldiers were given immunity for their previous acts under the controversial Charter for Peace and National Reconciliation.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Towards the end of his second term, Bouteflika amended the constitution to allow himself to run for a third term in 2009; to no one's surprise, he won the ensuing election, with a very low turnout, according to the opposition and the US Embassy.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Seventy percent of Algeria's population is less than 30 years old.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Consequent high levels of youth unemployment, coupled with corruption and widespread poverty, are seen as reasons for dissatisfaction.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The leader of the Rally for Culture and Democracy, Saïd Sadi, claimed that during 2010, there were "9,700 riots and [instances of] unrests" in Algeria.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Some protests were about issues such as education and health care, as well as rampant corruption.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 29 December 2010, clashes with police were reported in Algiers during protests about the lack of housing.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] At least 53 people were reported to have been injured and another 29 were arrested.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In 2011, prices of basic foodstuffs rose significantly in Algeria, in line with global trends but also reflecting newly imposed regulations.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Unprecedented protests in neighbouring Tunisia over unemployment were already being reported, contributing to the mood.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Between 3 and 10 January, riots and protests broke out across most Algerian towns, triggered by large increases in the prices of basic foods including oil, sugar, and flour.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] While localised riots have been a frequent occurrence in Algeria since 2005, this set of riots was the first to spread across most regions of the country simultaneously rather than being confined to a particular area.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] By 10 January they were limited to a few towns, but continued in those towns.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] More organised efforts to demonstrate on 11 January in Algiers were suppressed vigorously by the police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Protests against the price increases started on 3 January, with protest in the Ras El Ain quarter of Oran, and in Fouka and Staoueli near Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 5 January, major riots broke out in several areas at once: in the Bab El Oued neighbourhood of the capital, Algiers, and nearby suburbs, as well as Algeria's second city, Oran, and other towns including Djelfa, Boumerdes, Annaba, and Tipaza.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The young men rioting blocked roads, burned tires, and sacked government buildings, protesting the sudden increase in the cost of living, the demolition of shantytowns, and broader issues such as unemployment.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] They were met by anti-riot forces, who attempted to disperse the crowds.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In Bab El Oued, shops and car showrooms were also targeted.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Former Islamic Salvation Front number two Ali Belhadj went to Bab El Oued to see the events and encourage the youths; he was arrested later that day, as were many other protesters and rioters.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Within days the riots spread to twenty-odd *wilayahs*, covering almost the whole of the north including the Kabylie region, as well as some towns in the Sahara, such as Ouargla and Bechar.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Government buildings, particularly town halls, were widely targeted, and shops in some areas were looted or burned; some of the looters carried swords.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Football matches scheduled for 7 and 8 January were cancelled.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 8 January, the government agreed to a temporary cut in taxes and duties on sugar and cooking oil.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Facebook and Twitter access were also restricted in some areas.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The rioting continued, at least up to 10 January in some places, such as the Bachdjarrah neighbourood in Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] By 11 January, the situation had calmed.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] An attempt to demonstrate on 11 January in Algiers, organised by the intercommunal committee of Ain Benian and Staoueli, was repressed vigorously by the police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In total, three demonstrators died, more than 800 people had been wounded, and at least 1,100 were arrested, many of them minors.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] While riots on this scale are unprecedented since the 1991 election, their wider political implications are not yet clear.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The rioters had no collective ties to any Algerian political party, organisation, or trade union, and some sources commented that they seemed to have no political slogans.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Agence France-Presse (AFP) has linked the January protests with events in Tunisia, stating, "In Tunisia, similar unrest sparked the overthrow of the government of Zine Al Abidine Ben Ali, whose 23 years in power ended with his flight to Saudi Arabia last Friday.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] As the widely reported protests sparked off by Mohamed Bouazizi's self-immolation in Tunisia began to have a clear impact on the Tunisian government, a wave of self-immolations swept Algeria.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] These individual acts of protest mostly took place in front of a government building following an unsuccessful approach to the authorities.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Four self-immolators have died of their burns so far.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] It began on 12 January, when 26-year-old Mohamed Aouichia set himself on fire in Bordj Menaiel in the compound of the *daira* building.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] He had been sharing a room of 30 square metres with seven other people, including his sister, since 2003; he had repeatedly approached local authorities to get on the social housing list and been rebuffed.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 13 January, Mohsen Bouterfif, a 37-year-old father of two, set himself on fire.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] He had gone with about twenty other youths to protest in front of the town hall of Boukhadra in Tebessa demanding jobs and houses, after the mayor refused to receive them.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] According to one testimony, the mayor shouted to them: "If you have courage, do like Bouazizi did, set yourself on fire!" His death was reported on 16 January, and about 100 youths protested his death causing the provincial governor to sack the mayor.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] However, hospital staff the following day claimed he was still alive, though in critical condition.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Al Jazeera described the suicide as "echoing the self-immolation that triggered the protests that toppled the leader of neighbouring Tunisia." He finally died on 24 January at a hospital in Annaba.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] These suicides were followed by dozens more attempted or successful self-immolations across the country, so far without triggering nationwide demonstrations, most of them after the Tunisian dictator Zine El Abidine Ben Ali fled his country on 14 January.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] A number of left-wing opposition parties, including the FFS, RCD, PLJ, and the Communist MDS, as well as the Algerian League for Human Rights (LADDH) and officially unrecognised unions, such as SATEF and SNAPAP, met on 20 January to discuss responses to the situation.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 21 January, several of them (excluding the FFS) formed the Coordination Nationale pour le Changement et la Démocratie (National Coordination for Change and Democracy), seeking systemic change within the country and calling (along with Rachad) for nationwide marches, starting 9 February.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The Interior Minister, Ould Kablia, responded that "No march would be authorised by the authorities in Algiers...
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Meanwhile, the mainly Kabyle-based secularist RCD party had announced plans for a march for democracy to be held on Saturday 22 January, despite being refused permission by the government under the state of emergency.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Prior to the March, RCD leader Saïd Sadi linked the planned march to the 2010–2011 Tunisian protests, stating, "If the opposition does not mobilise the crowds, we believe that we will have more devastating events than what happened in Tunisia.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Some demonstrators waved the Tunisian flag, alluding to the protests which had brought down Ben Ali.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Would-be demonstrators coming from Tizi Ouzou were prevented from reaching the scene by the police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 22 January, 20,000 police officers stopped all protests.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In the ensuing clash five people were killed and more than 800 others hurt.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 23 January, the FFS and LADDH jointly issued a demand for the release of the demonstrators arrested in early January, in Tizi-Ouzou and elsewhere; students of Tizi-Ouzou announced plans for a march on 1 February demanding their release and economic development for Kabylie.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 29 January, the RCD organised a march of over ten thousand people (according to the organisers) in the city of Bejaia, to demand more freedom and democracy.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On the same day President Abdelaziz Bouteflika signaled at a meeting with government ministers his intention to lift the 19-year-old state of emergency in the "very near future", in what was seen as an attempt to quell opposition demands.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Reportedly, he also urged the cabinet to adopt measures to promote job creation and said Algeria's TV and radio should give airtime to all political parties.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 4 February, Al Jazeera reported that demonstrations were planned for 12 February.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] However, it was reported to have been observed in only 22 of the country's 48 provinces.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The day after Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak resigned, the protest gained new currency.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The protests were organised by the nascent National Co-ordination for Change and Democracy, an umbrella group of opposition parties, civil society groups and unofficial unions.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The police blocked all entry points into Algiers and put in a security cordon around May First Square in central Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] All opposition rallies were banned by the government, though at least 2,000 protesters forced their way through the security cordon around the Square to join other demonstrators.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Though minor protests occurred earlier in the day, most protesters came out after noon; several thousand protestors clashed with about 30,000 police at May First Square in central Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Police fired tear gas on the protesters and arrested hundreds to possibly more than a 10,000 people, including human rights activists and trade union members.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The Algerian League for the Defense of Human Rights said that up to 28,000 police officers were deployed in Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Many people, including a member of the People's National Assembly, Boubkeur Derguini of the RCD, were injured.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Protesters had hoped to stay the night at the main square.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] At almost 19:30, *Thomson Reuters* reported hundreds of people were leaving the demonstrations after about three hours and that the police opened their cordon to let them pass.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] It also said that about 200 young men from a poor neighbourhood stayed on and that some of them threw objects at the police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Protests were also reported in Constantine, Annaba, and Oran.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] There were reports of internet services like Twitter, Facebook and the wider internet to have been disrupted or shut down, however, *Renesys* denied this had taken place.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] He added that 90-year-old human rights activist Ali Yahia Abdelnour was "manhandled by the police" and that the protesters were not "an organised demonstration.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Elias Filali reported that police had used tear gas to disperse protesters and to evict families who had occupied newly constructed homes overnight in Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 14 February, Foreign Minister Mourad Medelci said the state of emergency would be lifted "within days." Two days later, Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahia announced the state of emergency would be lifted by the end of February.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Former FLN leader Abdelhamid Mehri called for true democracy, saying the current regime was incapable of solving the country's problems.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 18 February, a date for which a *Facebook* group had called for protests, police with water cannons were deployed in the main crossroads of Algiers.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Thousands turned out in Algiers for protests but were unable to take control of the main square.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The government officially announced the end of the emergency rule.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The country's council of ministers adopted a law revoking the 1993 decree that prolonged a state of emergency originally instituted the previous year, stating that the "law will come into effect as soon as its imminent publication in the official journal".
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The state of emergency in the country was officially lifted after being published in the country's official journal, responding to one of the main demands of the protesters.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The move legalizes protests outside the capital of Algiers, as long as the government is notified of planned demonstrations at least three days in advance.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] According to the country's interior minister, Dahou Ould Kabila, protests are still banned within Algiers because of security concerns; he said that "Algiers is targeted by leaders of terrorist groups [because] it gives them media impact.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Protests continue throughout Algiers, although it is reported that the government has been keeping the country stable, although this momentary peace is expected to end soon.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Meanwhile, Algeria's oldest opposition party, Socialist Forces Front, has urged Algerians to engage in a "peaceful struggle" for change in the nation.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 7 March, thousands of community police rallied in the capital Algiers despite a protest ban in the city, accusing the government of ingratitude, and insisting thousands of their colleagues have been killed or injured fighting Islamist violence.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Demanding better pay and pensions, they got all the way to the Parliament building.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In Algiers, small group of around 150 or so threw Molotov cocktails at much larger crowd of police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 23 March, police in the Algiers suburb of Oued Koriche used tear gas on Wednesday to disperse a crowd of young men who threw stones and Molotov cocktails trying to stop bulldozers from demolishing dozens of illegally built homes.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Five police officers were injured in the rioting, during which rioters threw bricks down on police from nearby rooftop and set fire to a car.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 15 April, in a long-awaited televised address, President Abdelaziz Bouteflika said he would seek constitutional amendments that would "reinforce representative democracy" and be submitted to parliament or to a referendum.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] He also proposed changes to laws on elections, the media or political parties.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 11 May, 1,500 Doctors attempted to march towards government buildings but were prevented by anti-riot police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In late February 2012, Algeria's major Islamist parties announced a coalition ahead of parliamentary elections.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] A leader of the Movement of Society for Peace called for more opposition parties to join the alliance "to give the best possible chance for the Arab Spring to happen in Algeria as well".
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The opposition group Rachad uploaded film of a non-violent demonstration of "more than 1000 people" demanding housing in the Said Hamdine neighbourhood of Algiers on 20 January, not widely reported.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 24 January, more than 500 people demonstrated in front of the *daira* building of Khemis El Khechna, demanding water and gas connection and better housing for their nearby hometowns, Chebacheb and El Kerma.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In Tizi Ouzou the same day, parents of youths detained in the protests of early January staged a sit-in in front of the wilaya seat building, demanding the release of their children, who were provisionally released the next day.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 25 January, the inhabitants of El Djezzar in Batna occupied their town hall, demanding a better road to their village.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On the same day, about a hundred inhabitants of Boutaleb near Chekfa blocked the main road, demanding gas and sewage connection for their town and better side roads.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 27 January, hundreds of inhabitants of Choukrane near Bouira closed the nearby national road (RN 29), demanding gas, water, a sewage system, and public lighting, as well as speed bumps to reduce traffic fatalities.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On the same day, dozens of unemployed youths blocked RN 12 in Naciria near Boumerdes using burning tyres and other objects, demanding jobs.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 30 January, unemployed youths closed the APC seat of Belaas in Ain Defla, demanding jobs (according to the mayor), as well as better water and road management.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On the same day, 600 factory workers demonstrated in front of the wilaya seat in Bouira, demanding to be re-hired by ENAD.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Also on the same day, unemployed youths in the wilaya of Ouargla demonstrated in Touggourt against the head of the local employment bureau, accused of favouritism.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 1 February, the people of Raffour in M'chedallah near Bouira blocked national route 26 with burning tyres, demanding public lighting, a sewage system, and town planning.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On the same day, the population of Tazgait in Mostaghanem closed their town hall, demanding that the mayor leave office for failing to do enough about the region's underdevelopment.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 7 February, youths at Toumiate in El Harrouch near Skikda blocked the national highway RN 3, and were attacked by riot police using tear gas.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 8 February, youths in Sidi Amar near Annaba demonstrated to demand jobs, blocking the road and burning tyres.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] From 6 to 9 February, protesters closed the national highway RN 26 at El Kseur near Bejaia, demanding their jobs back or better compensation after the EPBTP milk factory where they were employed made them redundant.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 8 and 9 February, youths in Naciria and Bordj-Menaiel attacked ANEM offices, confronted police, and closed the national highway RN 12, protesting unemployment and unfulfilled government promises of jobs.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 13 February, a crowd of youths gathered in front of the Annaba wilaya office demanding the 7000 jobs they had previously been promised, and greeted the governor with stone-throwing when he came out.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] One attempted suicide, but was dissuaded by his brother.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 14 February, hundreds of youths protested over unemployment in Akbou; about 30 were hurt in clashes with the police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 16 February, youths in Tadmait (Tizi-Ouzou) went out on the streets demanding jobs, blocking the roads (including RN 12) with burning tires and damaging the APC office.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Five of them were arrested after confrontations with anti-riot police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 17 February, about 500 youths demonstrated in front of the same daira office.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Another 100 unemployed youths demonstrated in nearby Touggourt, in front of the local office of the National Employment Agency.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 17 February, the Annaba wilaya offices were again targeted by demonstrators demanding jobs.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 21 February, hundreds of students protesting in front of the Ministry of Higher Education against the new LMD system were dispersed forcibly by police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In Ammal (Boumerdes), demonstrators closed the local APC offices, demanding better housing.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 23 February, villagers from nearby Imaghzarene closed the daira offices of Draa El Mizan, demanding paving, public lighting, gas, more housing, and a clinic for their town.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] At Ammi Moussa (Relizane) dozens of youths gathered to blockade the town hall, demanding that the president and secretary-general of the APC resign.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On the same day, doctors in the Sidi Bel Abbes maternity ward staged a sit-in in protest against the lack of pharmaceutical supplies, which they said was preventing them from carrying out operations.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Bouzareah university students announced a strike demanding greater security at the university after a woman student was attacked by unknown assailants, who slashed her face, on campus grounds.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 24 February, unemployed youths gathered in front of the mayoralty of Sidi Lakhdar near Mostaganem, after blocking the road (RN11) the previous day; they left when the mayor promised to review the housing lists.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In Djelida (Ain Defla), the same day, about 500 people closed the APC offices, demanding jobs and protesting at the allocation of 117 new jobs to people from outside the region.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 10 January, Algerians protested in Laghouat over housing, infrastructure, and treatment of the elderly by police.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] The police used tear gas to disperse the protesters.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] After security forces question three youths who were eating lunch in the Kabylie region during Ramadan, about 300 others joined a protest lunch against the mandatory nature of fasting during the month.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In reaction to the protests of early January, starting 8 January the government decreased the prices of essential foods.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Over following weeks it increased wheat supplies.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 3 February Bouteflika announced plans to lift the emergency law, which prohibits protests without a permit, and substitute for it new anti-terrorism laws, but said that protests would remain illegal in Algiers in any case "for well-known reasons of public order".
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] He also announced new measures to create jobs and that state-run television and radio should be open to all political parties.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] On 14 February, his foreign minister Mourad Medelci repeated the promise to end the state of emergency law, saying it would happen by the end of the month. on 22 February the cabinet voted to lift the emergency law.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] It also voted on a measure to alleviate unemployment.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] In efforts to discourage the protests organised by the CNCD, the authorities played up the role of the RCD, a mainly Kabyle party unpopular elsewhere in the country, within them; while this tactic had some success, it did not stop demonstrators from turning out in some non-Kabyle cities.
[src:ancient-carthage/2010-2011-algerian-protests] Regional financial stock market indices fell on 20 February on concern of spreading instability.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The events came as part of the aftermath of the Tunisian Revolution which ousted the country's longtime president Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, followed by a general election which saw Ennahda win a plurality alongside Moncef Marzouki's allied Congress for the Republic (CPR).
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The crisis gradually subsided when Prime Minister Ali Laarayedh resigned and a new constitution was adopted in January 2014.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Many incidents fueled the protests including the assassination of prominent secular leaders Chokri Belaid on 6 February 2013 and Mohamed Brahmi on 25 July.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Other factors include the government's failure to deal with the rise of hardline Salafist groups including Ansar al-Sharia which is widely believed to be behind the assassinations, as well as many other attacks on security personnel and state institutions.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] This prompted the government to list the group as a terrorist organization amid growing pressure by opposition groups.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] In exchange for Ennahda's resignation, the opposition agreed to pass a constitution in which freedom of worship will be guaranteed but in the same time gave a greater role to religion in public life than before.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] This was followed by the suspension then dissolution of the former ruling RCD party and the resignation of Prime Minister Mohamed Ghannouchi amid further public pressure.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The Ennahda Movement had long been banned in the political spectrum by former President Ben Ali, most notably in the 1989 elections where some of its members had to run independently due to government repression.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Two years after the elections Ben Ali jailed nearly 25,000 of its activists with Ennahda militants responding by attacking the ruling party's headquarters killing one person and splashing acid on others.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Following the revolution, it described itself to be a "moderate Islamist" party by advocating democracy and recognizing political pluralism and dialogue with the West.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Its supporters back then regarded the party as an example of how a balance can be struck between modernity and Islamism while its critics viewed it as a threat to secularism in Tunisia, which was often regarded as the most secular Arab state.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] In addition, leading Ennahda figures have repeatedly tried to reassure worrying Tunisians that it would protect civil rights and democracy.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] However, the movement was accused to have been shaped by Qutbism and is highly influenced by the Muslim Brotherhood of Egypt and many of its secular opponents pointing out to acid attacks on female students in the 1980s for dressing "indecently" as a warning sign from Islamist repression.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] It is also believed that Rashid al-Ghannushi himself, the co-founder of the party had a long history of violent thinking.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Following Ben Ali's ouster, the party was legalized and Ghannushi was welcomed by a crowd of 1,000 people upon his return to the country after 22 years of exile in Europe.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Ghannushi later formed an alliance called the Troika with two secular political parties which are Moncef Marzouki's CPR and the Democratic Forum for Labour and Liberties.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Both murders were blamed on Islamic extremists with Boubacar Hakim, a hardline Salafist who is being sought for under suspicion of smuggling weapons from Libya, as the prime suspect.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] On 6 February 2013, Chokri Belaid was leaving his house on his way to the headquarters of the Tunisian General Labour Union for a meeting with its secretary general when he was shot four times by a gunman who later took off on a motorbike driven by a second accomplice.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Belaid was quickly rushed to the nearest clinic but the doctors were unable to save him and he was pronounced dead at the clinic.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Current secretary general of Belaid's party and leader of the Popular Front, Ziad Lakhdhar, said in a statement: "Chokri Belaid was killed today by four bullets to the head and chest ... doctors told us that he has died.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] It was also reported that Belaid had received several death threats prior to his assassination with many of his supporters blaming Ennahda for failing to protect him following those threats and an incident targeting fellow party members a week earlier.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The night before the incident, he appeared in a political talk show on Tunisia's Nessma TV and said; "Rashid Ghannushi considers the leagues to be the conscience of the nation, so the defense of the authors of violence is clear.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] All those who oppose Ennahda become the targets of violence." Following his assassination, thousands of demonstrators gathered outside the Interior Ministry building in Tunis carrying Belaid's coffin and shouted *"The people demand the fall of the regime"*.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The day turned violent when some of the protesters threw rocks with the police using tear gas to disperse the rallies.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] On 25 July 2013, Mohamed Brahmi was shot dead in his car in front of his home in Tunis by unknown gunmen on a motorbike in front of his wife Mbarka and his daughter Belkis who were both shocked after the tragedy.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The incident occurred on the day Tunisia was set to celebrate Republic Day when the country was celebrating the 56th anniversary of the beginning of Habib Bourguiba's presidency.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] They were also joined by his wife and daughter in front of the hospital where he died.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Hundreds of supporters also protested in Brahmi's hometown of Sidi Bouzid.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] During Brahmi's funeral, protesters called for the government to be toppled, while police fired tear gas on them.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] According to a statement made by the Tunisian Prosecutor regarding the autopsy of Brahmi's corpse; "The deceased had been hit with fourteen gunshots: six in his torso and eight in his left leg".
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Brahmi's killing was condemned by many international leaders including UN Human Rights chief Navi Pillay and President of the European Parliament Martin Schulz who said in a statement; "I am deeply saddened to learn of the despicable murder of our colleague Mohamed Brahmi.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Investigations had been issued following both assassinations and Interior Minister Lotfi Ben Jeddou announced at a news conference that the same 9mm automatic weapon that killed Belaid also killed Brahmi.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The left-wing leader maintained that Belhadj apparently intended to carry out terrorist attacks in Tunisia, and trained the Ansar al-Sharia cell that killed the opposition politicians, all under close observation by Ennahda leaders Rashid al-Ghannushi, Hamadi Jebali and Samir Dilou, among others.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] On 19 September 2013, Tunisia's interior minister told lawmakers the CIA informed authorities Brahmi was a target and said there'd been a "failure" in the security services' response.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] He announced an investigation had been opened.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The post-revolution Tunisia has witnessed an unprecedented rise in extremism through increasing militant activity, weapons smuggling from Libya and involvement in the political scene.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] They range from self-claimed moderate parties like Ennahda to the more hard-line Ansar al-Sharia and Hizb ut-Tahrir.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Most of them denounced violence as a way to reach their goals and have advocated democracy.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] However, some have been engaged in numerous clashes with security forces mainly in the south and north-west of the country resulting in numerous casualties on both sides in a conflict that is often related to the wider Maghreb insurgency.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Several attacks by extremist factions took place in the Mount Chaambi national park on the border with Algeria.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] On 29 July 2013, a military convoy was ambushed by militants resulting in a number of deaths with many of the victims found beheaded and others mutilated.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] A week later, the Tunisian Armed Forces responded with an army offensive and air strikes to clear out the mountains of Islamist elements responsible for the assaults.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] One of the most prominent extremist organizations is Ansar al-Sharia in Tunisia (AST) that was highly involved in the political scene before being listed by the government as a terrorist group.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] The group was founded in April 2011 by Abu Iyadh al-Tunisi, who had previously co-founded the Tunisian Combat Group (TCG) in Afghanistan with Tarek Maaroufi.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] Unlike Al-Qaeda and other like-minded groups in the Arab world, the AST claims to be non-violent and engages in charitable activity as a way of gaining support providing food, medicine and clothing while at the same time preaching mainstream Salafist thinking.
[src:ancient-carthage/2013-2014-tunisian-political-crisis] They have also carried out attacks on art exhibits, premises that sell alcohol and ransacked ancient shrines it considered un-Islamic.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Carthage was settled around 814 BC by merchants from Tyre, a leading Phoenician city-state located in present-day Lebanon.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] In the 7th century BC, following Phoenicia's conquest by the Neo-Assyrian Empire, Carthage became independent of its eastern neighbors.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Leveraging its naval power, Carthage then began to grow a vast patchwork of colonies, vassals, and satellite states until it was the economic and political hegemon of the western Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] By 300 BC, Carthage controlled the coast of northwestern Africa, southern and eastern Iberia, and the islands of Sicily, Sardinia, Corsica, Malta, and the Balearic Islands.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Tripoli remained *de facto* autonomous under the authority of local Libyco-Phoenicians, a mixed culture of local Libyans and Phoenicians, who paid nominal tribute.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Among the ancient world's largest and richest cities, Carthage's strategic location provided access to abundant fertile land and major maritime trade routes that reached West Asia and Northern Europe.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] This commercial empire was secured by one of the largest and most powerful navies in classical antiquity, and an army composed heavily of foreign mercenaries and auxiliaries, which included Iberians, Balearics, Gauls, Britons, Sicilians, Italians, Greeks, Numidians, and Libyans.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Carthage's unique system of government combined at different times elements of primitive democracy, oligarchy, and republicanism, including early examples of separation of powers.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] As the dominant power in the western Mediterranean, Carthage inevitably came into conflict with many neighbours and rivals, from the Berbers of North Africa to the nascent Roman Republic.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Following centuries of conflict with the Sicilian Greeks, its growing competition with Rome culminated in the Punic Wars (264–146 BC), which saw some of the largest and most sophisticated battles in antiquity.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Carthage narrowly avoided destruction after the Second Punic War, but was destroyed by the Romans in 146 BC after the Third Punic War.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] The Romans later founded a new city in its place.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] All remnants of Carthaginian civilization came under Roman rule by the 1st century AD, and Rome subsequently became the dominant Mediterranean power, paving the way for the Roman Empire.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Despite having been one of the most influential civilizations of antiquity, Carthage is mostly remembered for its long and bitter conflict with Rome.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Due to the destruction of virtually all Carthaginian texts after the Third Punic War, much of what is known about its civilization comes from Roman and Greek sources, many of which were written during or after the Punic Wars, and to varying degrees were influenced by the hostilities.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Popular and scholarly attitudes towards Carthage historically reflected the prevailing Greco-Roman view, though archaeological research since the late 19th century has helped shed more light and nuance on Carthaginian civilization.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] The name *Carthage* /ˈkɑːrθɪdʒ/ is the Early Modern anglicisation of Middle French *Carthage* /kar.taʒ/, from Latin *Carthāgō* and *Karthāgō* (cf.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Greek *Karkhēdōn* (Καρχηδών) and Etruscan **Carθaza*) from the Punic *qrt-ḥdšt*, vocalised by Brett Mulligan as *Qart-Ḥadašt* (Punic: 𐤒𐤓𐤕𐤟𐤇𐤃𐤔𐤕, lit.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] It is unclear what term, if any, the Carthaginians used to refer to themselves.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Ancient Egyptian accounts suggest the people from the region identified as *Kenaani* or *Kinaani*, equivalent to Canaanite.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] A passage from Augustine claims that if asked, the people of Africa (modern day Tunisia) would reply that they are *Chanani* (Canaanites) in Phoenician.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] Despite that being almost universally accepted by scholars, some still dismiss Augustine's claims.
[src:ancient-carthage/ancient-carthage] For example, Josephine Quinn doubts the claim's truthfulness.
